hands_on_practices.solution:
We have 
$$\kappa=\kappa_1+\kappa_2,\quad \kappa_i=C_i\rho^{a_i}T^{b_i}.$$ 
Thus
$$\frac{\partial\ln\kappa}{\partial\ln\rho}
=\frac{\rho}{\kappa}\frac{\partial\kappa}{\partial\rho}
=\frac{a_1\kappa_1+a_2\kappa_2}{\kappa_1+\kappa_2},$$
$$\frac{\partial\ln\kappa}{\partial\ln T}
=\frac{b_1\kappa_1+b_2\kappa_2}{\kappa_1+\kappa_2}.$$
Hence
$$D
=\frac{a_1\kappa_1+a_2\kappa_2}{\kappa_1+\kappa_2}
+(\gamma_{ad}-1)\frac{b_1\kappa_1+b_2\kappa_2}{\kappa_1+\kappa_2}
=0.$$
Multiplying through by $\kappa_1+\kappa_2$ gives
$$\bigl[a_1+(\gamma_{ad}-1)b_1\bigr]\kappa_1
+\bigl[a_2+(\gamma_{ad}-1)b_2\bigr]\kappa_2=0.$$
Solving for the ratio $\kappa_2/\kappa_1$ at marginal stability,
$$\frac{\kappa_2}{\kappa_1}
=-\frac{a_1+(\gamma_{ad}-1)b_1}{a_2+(\gamma_{ad}-1)b_2}.$$
